Text.Value: Slaying as great an enemy of my people as Minsc would normally be a great victory, but he was just another puppet of the cult.
You and Viconia don't seem all that different.
She has been exiled from the Underdark for more than a century. She would not have survived if she were not willing to fight.
We have done Umberlee's will. Now let us never return to the depths of her domain again.

EditorData.NodeContext: closing statement of a quest completed rather than a new adventure - the Umberlee section is done at this point, she's reflecting

Text.Value: Karlach is willing to become illithid so that we need not make that sacrifice. We should not stand in her way.
Killing one's parents can be an important rite of passage - a usurpation of their place in society.

EditorData.NodeContext: genuinely believes this to be true

Text.Value: My memories of this place are grim. The reality is worse.

EditorData.NodeContext: horrified awe, in a mind flayer colony

Text.Value: Strange to say, but you may be right.
Would that be the same Mystra that is responsible for his plight? I am sure she has his best interests at heart.
That was horrendous. I would rather yank Tiamat's tail than travel beneath the water again.

EditorData.NodeContext: TEE-uh-mat - dragon god. The party just travelled underwater, and Minthara HATED it.

Text.Value: I will gladly help destroy your enemies, Astarion. But do not expect me to call you Lord.
I will gladly help Astarion to destroy his enemies, but I hope he does not expect me to call him Lord.
I only survived Orin's sadistic games because she allowed me to. Even if we find her soon, I doubt the child Yenna will be in one piece.
'Beware loud men with purple scalps and ugly rodents, for they think of you as evil, and will kill you on sight.'

EditorData.NodeContext: not putting on an exaggerated voice, but she is quoting a warning from her childhood, told to her by an elder.

Text.Value: For freedom. Bhaal only wanted me to serve him.
She will take our side because it best protects her interests.
She will be ready to right when we need her, I am sure of it.
Shadowheart may not have gained status from her parents' death, but she has freed herself from Shar's influence. There is comfort in that.
We have done Umberlee's will. Now let us stay far from the depths of her dread domain.

EditorData.NodeContext: closing statement of a quest completed rather than a new adventure - the Umberlee section is done at this point, she's reflecting

Text.Value: It was quite the scandal, and I was young enough that it left an impression on me.
Do you have any idea where we'll find Balthazar?
We do not need to trust Viconia, we only need to know which side she will take in this conflict, and that is clear.
The memories are as dark and elusive as a cloaker.

EditorData.NodeContext: cloaker is an underdark creature - it's a familiar phrase to her, like 'as sliippery as an eel'.

Text.Value: Must you always refer to me as 'the wizard'. My name is Gale.
Good. We will both have our vengeance on Orin. All that we need argue about is which one of us has the pleasure of opening her throat.
They dare not enter. Naturally, anything that frightens them intrigues me. We should investigate.
Don't get me wrong - I'm glad the fucker is dead. It's just... hard.
Maybe you're right.
Do not let the laws or scruples of inferior minds stand in your way.
It is not only a hostile place, it is a hidden place. My family have a saying: Let the first blood you draw be your enemy's end.
We will regret his absence.

EditorData.NodeContext: pragmatic rather than sad, speaking of the loss of Astarion

Text.Value: I'm glad you see reason. To martyr oneself for the fickle gods is insanity.
If we stop to talk, we will be food for the fish.
I would advise a thorough search of Balthazar's chambers at the tower before delving into the mausoleum. Any knowledge we can find may arm us for what is to come.
You will realise, soon, how little you need her. Or you will die, mourning a loss that has no meaning.
We must destroy him in his lair before he completes the rite, and becomes a threat not just to Astarion, but to our own designs on the city.
Her death will yield me a great reward.
Where should we go next?
While she lives, Orin will continue to terrorise us, and soon she will make good on her threats. She thinks we are weak, afraid, vulnerable.
Despite my antipathy toward Shar and her devotees, I feel honoured to fight alongside a Dark Justiciar. Their power is legendary.
A monster may be precisely what we need if we are to survive what is coming.

EditorData.NodeContext: matter of fact assessment of the situation

Text.Value: But I do not understand why you killed the cleric.
There's still hope that we'll find a way to fix her heart.
We must pick up his trail at the Thorm Mausoleum.
Distancing them from the conflict is the best way to ensure they live long lives.
Do you know anything about the House of Healing?
We need to prove her wrong.
No matter - they will all be disappointed. Lord Ao the Overgod could not take it from us.
You are Gale, Wizard of Waterdeep, and with or without Mystra, you are as great a practitioner of magic as anyone I have ever known.
If not here in the tower, then close by. Surely you can feel its presence too?
Even the intervention of their gods can't save these chosen from our vengeance. We defy divinity.

EditorData.NodeContext: having just killed the Chosen of a god - delighted and slightly in awe of what the party have achieved

Text.Value: Something lingers there. Something that inspires terror among those cultists unfortunate enough to have glimpsed it while patrolling the area.
Good. I have little of it to spare.
We need to destroy the Absolute, no matter what it is.
She is a fierce ally, and has survived great torments and challenges already. We would be fortunate to have her with us until the end.
Disturbing. I'd rather forget my past than embrace it.
We are unstoppable. I feel like we could conquer the hells.

EditorData.NodeContext: delighted, having just slain a devil in his own home

Text.Value: If you want empty platitudes and a rousing, gallant speech, young Wyll Ravengard may be able to provide it.
But you may still be effective, even in your diminished state, and we have precious few allies in this battle.
We came here to find Ketheric and the Absolute, not Wyll's devil-mistress. We must press on.
This city has one too many self-righteous Ravengards. I would have preferred Wyll cut his family ties.
Our victory is at hand. We cannot falter now, no matter what is required of us.
My mother taught me to talk, to walk, and then to kill. I still hope to thank her by teaching her how to die one day.
Without the promise of your blood, I fear you have lost part of your strength that you can never regain.
What do you have against Viconia?
It is better to accept that, and to make sure she is ready to fight to the last.
I believe we are only beginning to understand what he is capable of.
Then you should reacquaint yourself with the taste of rat-blood, since you may well be a spawn again before long.
If any child of mine spoke of me as disrespectfully as Jaheira's offspring speak of her, their lives would be exceedingly short.
Talk to Jaheira if you wish to hear tales of heroic Bhaalspawn and their past victories. She likes filling peoples' heads with noble ideals.
Your concern is for the Absolute rather than me. Touching.
I will fight alongside Minsc, but if he so much as refers to my butt, let alone attempts to kick it, I will skewer that damned hamster of his.

EditorData.NodeContext: irritated - the 'butt' mention is a reference to Minsc talking of 'kicking butts' constantly

Text.Value: He gave you an opportunity to embrace your savage birthright and to tame it.
I am loathe to admit it, but if we can pacify Minsc he may be a worthy companion.

EditorData.NodeContext: reluctant to admit a 'good guy' is a worthy ally

Text.Value: We cannot allow Gale to go through with Elminster's ludicrous plan. Destroying the Absolute before we fully understand it would be madness.

EditorData.NodeContext: the 'plan' is for Gale to destroy the absolute - Minthara is dead set against this

Text.Value: Allying with that maggot-infested wretch makes my skin crawl, but if he can help us to secure the relic, so be it.
If you have any strength left, bring it to the battlefield. You certainly do not have enough to share my bed anymore.

EditorData.AnimationTags: *REUSE* [MINTHARA] end of HUM_F_Rig_SCENE_DEN_dismissed_KAG_angry for walk away., *REUSE* alternate: TIF_F_Rig_SCENE_DEN_Arka_StrideAway<CodyM>
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: walks away from the party in disgust

Text.Value: I don't care about your approval.
The Orphic Hammer may be the key to our survival. I for one would be glad to avoid complete ceremorphosis.
It would have been a mercy - at least I'd have been spared this drivel.
I have been watching you more closely than ever since the night we were forced to restrain you.

EditorData.NodeContext: warning - she's concerned about the player's behaviour

Text.Value: I was ordered to. By my butler.
Don't be naive. Half of the people here have been greedily eyeing our belongings since we arrived.
It is frustrating that he is so incurious. I believe he is capable of greater things than he realises.
I prefer strategy to instincts and impulses.
Where can we find Ketheric?
He was looking for the Nightsong inside the temple. We should return there and see what we can discover.
It's not like you to be sentimental.
Did you spend much time in these lands when you served the Absolute?
This rite of ascendance suggests he is far more impressive and ambitious than I realised.
She infests your notion of the weave, just as the Absolute's voice infested my thoughts.
Then we have something in common, wizard, for I do not care about yours.
All things considered, my relationship with her may not be the best model to follow.

EditorData.NodeContext: awkwardly acknowledging the dysfunctional nature of her relationship with her mother. Can see the humour in it.

Text.Value: I love you, isn't that a greater power than anything?
My mother visited, during one of her grand tours of the surface world. She claimed the streets were almost as varied and full of danger as those in Duthcloim.

EditorData.NodeContext: DUTH-cloin (rhymes with truth,rjhymes with loin) - a district of Menzoberranzan, Minthara's home city. Literally translates as 'manyfolk', a diverse district.

Text.Value: I am concerned for Karlach. She is strong, but even her courage may falter now that she knows how little time remains to her.

EditorData.NodeContext: has just found out Karlach is living on borrowed time - genuine concern

Text.Value: He is wise to reject it, and to seek Mystra's aid instead.
We believed we were all victims of the cult of the Absolute, but now we learn that one of us was an architect of this grand religious hoax.
We know that power has its source in a relic - the Nightsong - and we know that Balthazar was responsible for its creation.
Unnerving though it is, if we are to face an elder brain, we could have no better ally than an illithid.

EditorData.logicalname: Topic 46 - In Astral Plane after Emperor

Text.Value: You're right. They should be ready to fight.
I'm not involving myself with any damned infernal rites.
It is sad to see how Jaheira has neglected her family. They should be prepared for the battle that is coming, or they may not survive it.

EditorData.NodeContext: after meeting Jaheira;s family - Minthara is concerned the youths are not prepared for war

Text.Value: I deal in reality, not idealism, so you will have to seek praise elsewhere.
Gothic. Decadent. Vulgar. I can see this place had quite the influence on your tastes, Astarion.
Gothic. Decadent. Vulgar. This place clearly had quite the influence on Astarion's tastes.
I had thought Cazador little more than a decadent slave-driver and stalker of the night.
This is it. The end of everything - or our moment of triumph.
It is amusing to hear that the Legendary Ranger has become as much a terror in his own city as he is in the Underdark.
Half of the children here are already mutilated by poverty and starvation.
Patricide is often the first step toward greatness, but I hope Wyll does not regret sacrificing his infernal powers.

EditorData.NodeContext: Wyll killed his father. Minthara sees the bright side in her evil way.She is very sincere about this.

Text.Value: Lae'zel risks everything with her childish rebellion.
No matter how desperate the fight becomes, stay the course. We will not fail. We will dominate.

EditorData.NodeContext: Determined, confident, reassuring her allies in a dark moment

Text.Value: You are a wizard, are you not? Surely you have an obligation to learn about the world and all of its mysteries rather than destroying them.
I am not opposed to killing an ally who has outlasted their use, but Astarion had become a formidable weapon.

EditorData.NodeContext: pragmatic rather than sad, speaking of the loss of Astarion

Text.Value: If it's congratulations you want, I am sure Karlach will provide. The language may be foul, but the feeling will be fair.
We're preparing for battle against an elder brain - this isn't the time for melodrama.
Myrkul, Bane, Bhaal, and now Shar? Are there any gods who do not want the Prism?

EditorData.NodeContext: listing off gods who are hunting the party, slightly bewildered but ready to take on all of them

Text.Value: Agreed. Leave the waters to the fish and the aboleths.

EditorData.NodeContext: B-o-leth- large underwater abomination, familiar to Minthara

Text.Value: Bhaal should be begging me to join his ranks.
I was unsure of our alliance with the Sharrans - betraying Shadowheart seemed a steep price to pay - but I accept the wisdom of it now.
You're wrong. I need Mystra.
Bhaal gave you an opportunity to embrace your savage birthright, and to tame it.
If you need a pat on the head and a scratch behind the ears, I am sure Minsc will provide. Boo has him well-trained.
There is danger on every corner.
It is the perfect time for whatever was between us to die.
If you want mindless praise and affection, find Scratch. He will nuzzle your hand and follow at your heel no matter how disappointing you are.
Neither the Zhentarim or the Guild are capable of running this city as they should.

EditorData.NodeContext: superiority complex kicking into high gear as she assesses the chriminal organisations that run the city

Text.Value: She's spent her life in conflict - it's natural she wants to protect them from that.
How small-minded. This is not about good or evil - this is about power. You rejected glory, and I reject you.
That was exciting. Where's your sense of adventure?
Hear me, wizard. You cannot go through with Elminster's ludicrous plan.

EditorData.NodeContext: speaking to Gale, annoyed with him

Text.Value: Now stop sulking and practise your spellcraft. We have a city to save, and an elder brain to master.

EditorData.NodeContext: just complimented Gale and is trying to ground him in reality again so he doesn't get too pompous, and so SHE doesn't seem too soft

Text.Value: I, for one, will miss the shadow curse. For all the pain it caused us, it did at least obscure the incessant sun.

EditorData.NodeContext: not entirely serious, but she is bitter about the 'incessant sun'. She has delicate skin!

Text.Value: You've never complimented me before.
You have seen a god reanimate the bones of his Chosen, you have seen an entity capable of commanding legions with a thought.
She won't give up as long as we support her.
You're right. A wizard should seek out new knowledge and power, whatever the source.
Sometimes I think you are quite mad. Other times I think you still hold on to a slim fragment of your sanity.
Any man who can resist being digested by a mimic may even give an elder brain food for thought.

EditorData.NodeContext: impressed by Minsc's resilience - play on words with food and digested is intentional.

Text.Value: This place is wondrous. A shame it is not ours to command.

EditorData.NodeContext: inside a factory producing military machines, admiring

Text.Value: How is it better? Mystra is magic. I'm nothing without her.
There was no honour in killing him while he did not know himself.
Any idea what we should expect to find at the Mausoleum?
It's hard to savour anything when your time is running out.
I must ask you something. First, let me make it clear that I do not object to the killing of Isobel, or the loss of Last Light.
You have seen the fires of the Hells, and the devils who dwell there.
We face a threat capable of eradicating this city - capable of eradicating us with a thought.
It's an impressive place.
The necromancer Balthazar should be our next target.
But if Balthazar's mission has taken him to the Mausoleum, we will find more there than bones and memories.
You would do better to harness the power of that shadow magic than to destroy it.
Are you so afraid that you cannot see what an opportunity this is? You could be our salvation.
You are welcome to explode wherever and whenever you please, as long as you do not destroy anything of value.
Allow me to process it for you.
The only reason you ever lost control is because you resisted the truth - rejected the glory of your true self.
I hope Elminster's message has not left you feeling dejected, wizard. It is better for you to be free of Mystra.
Vengeance is a bitter pill for kind souls. I pity Karlach that she could not savour Gortash's death.

EditorData.NodeContext: after seeing Karlach break down in tears after getting revenge on Gortash. GEnuinely sad

Text.Value: You rejected the extraordinary, and for what?
If the devil truly holds an artefact that can free Prince Orpheus, we cannot ignore it. Any ally who can aid us against the brain is worth having.
Even when the faithful abandon them, sacred places do not lose their power. Be on your guard.
Continue to indulge your curiosity in the pursuit of new power, and I might deign to remember it.
I would prefer to cut your throat, and finish what Bhaal could not.
The darkness here reminds me of home - so does the danger. Be on your guard.
If you cannot see the appeal of bloodshed and danger, perhaps you should retire from adventuring and farm root vegetables for the rest of your days.
Doubtful. Like everything else in these lands, its original purpose has been corrupted by the shadows.
When I see you squandering your talents to serve a god rather than indulging your intellectual curiosity, I cannot help but be disappointed.
Ketheric is working from the same principle. He raises his army in shadow so none may know the extent of his power until it is too late to resist.
Ah, the wizard. I could not help but notice that you have been exploring new avenues of knowledge recently - I approve.

EditorData.NodeContext: opening phrase is a greeting to Gale - she doesn't know his name. He's just 'the wizard'.

Text.Value: Oh? Are you suddenly incapable of touching the weave? Do your spells fizzle before you can cast them? I think not.

EditorData.NodeContext: reverse psychology - she's trying to cheer Gale up

Text.Value: Something is different about you. Did you change your diet?
Shadowheart looks different. A change of diet, perhaps?

EditorData.NodeContext: Shadowheart has changed her hairstyle. Minthara genuinely doesn't know what's different.

Text.Value: I do not mean to diminish her achievements entirely though.
I think he is beyond the need to sleep and dream, just as he is beyond death. His time is occupied in higher matters.
It must be hard to savour anything when your time is running out.
Were you indoctrinated in the tower when you first came to the cult?
Good riddance. We'll be better off without her.
For the thrill of it.
Wyll would be wiser to leverage his family name for a position of power in Baldur's Gate. The hells can have him for all I care.
Shar was right to punish your transgression, child, but she should not have discarded you so cruelly.
Shar has discarded young Shadowheart like a broken toy. The gods are ever fickle.
The relic Balthazar seeks may be the key to this. He is not only Ketheric's closest advisor, but an accomplished necromancer.
The wizard has become slightly less insipid and a little more insidious of late. The change suits him.

EditorData.NodeContext: speaking of Gale, who is turning to the dark side

Text.Value: I have heard much of the cunning and caution of the Harpers. Clearly those tales were exaggerated.
What you call 'corruption', I call 'empowerment'.

EditorData.NodeContext: you say potato, I say potahto - but much more sinister of course

Text.Value: When I was held in the prison, I felt an overwhelming hunger, as if I were suspended above a great maw, eager to consume and absorb me.
I don't care what you think of me.
To serve the gods is always a choice, and to martyr oneself for them is insanity.
She has made you believe that you need her. That is what the gods do. In truth, she is not so different to the Absolute.
I am right.
We need to get out of here.
I'm not convinced she will help. She's hardly trustworthy.
Astarion was a powerful ally. It was foolish to sacrifice him for the favour of the craven Gur.
This is none of your business, Minthara. You don't know what you're talking about.
We can trust Karlach to do what is needed, but she must do it quickly.

EditorData.logicalname: Topic 174 - Need Karlach MindFlayer with Stones

Text.Value: For her sake, we should not. And besides, celebrations can come later - our fight is not over yet.

EditorData.NodeContext: after seeing Karlach break down in tears after getting revenge on Gortash. GEnuinely sad

Text.Value: Your past is revealed to us, Chosen of Bhaal. How does it feel, to know who you truly are?
I had thought Cazador little more than a decadent slave-driver and stalker of the night.
Their entire network in the city has been infiltrated and undone by a handful of imposters.

EditorData.NodeContext: surprised by how feeble the harper 'network' is.

Text.Value: Do what must be done. Become illithid, and we can end this.
I don't need your pity.
I would live forever if I could. Death is not rest or relief, it is only ever a form of defeat.
I want to take back my rightful place.
It was the only way to gain control of myself.
Lae'zel was wise to slay the githyanki rebel. We have already angered enough gods, we need not anger Vlaakith as well.
If I take its head, how will it learn from its mistakes?

EditorData.NodeContext: with a smile on the first phrase - a sick joke

Text.Value: I fear these new powers may corrupt his connection to the weave.
He is becoming more formidable.
This doesn't mean I'm good now, simply that I'm in control.
Dame Aylin is likely to tear him in half if she learns of his plans. We should tell her immediately.
Access is forbidden to all but his closest advisors. Even if we were among them, it would be suicidal to approach him while his power holds.
I resisted the god of murder. You should be congratulating me, not complaining.
We should hang up their remains as a warning to Cazador that Astarion is under our protection.
If you believe love is a greater power than all of that, you are stupider than I feared.
Show no mercy. We must cleanse this place.
Once she is dead, we can seize control not only the Temple of Bhaal, but the cult of the Absolute as well.
These new abilities may corrupt him.
Speak quietly. Shar's agents will be listening.
To kill Ketheric, we must strip him of the power that keeps death from claiming him.
Yes. And also more intriguing.
Ketheric himself was entombed there for decades. An undying man, sealed in darkness with the bones of his ancestors.
He would be unwise to dabble in shadow magic.
Ketheric recognised me as a soldier, and took me into his army immediately.
I always thought wizards were curious beings. Your attitude is rather dull.
We have attracted Umberlee's wrath. Let us be sure not to take any long sea voyages in the near future.

EditorData.NodeContext: closing statement of a quest completed rather than a new adventure - the Umberlee section is done at this point, she's reflecting

Text.Value: Please don't mutilate any children, Minthara.
Where Ketheric has gone, madness and horror await. Steel yourself - we must follow.

EditorData.NodeContext: trepidation and a little excitement - she's looking forward to killing Ketheric, even though she's frightened of what is to come

Text.Value: The elder brain is close. Be ready for anything.
Lorroakan's the type to cower behind contraptions and cantrips rather than facing danger. He has about as much spine as a gray ooze.
He had become a monster.
You helped to create this conspiracy. That means you may be the best person to help us control it, and the key to our victory.
Are you suggesting I perform the rite myself?
I would prefer if you informed me of your intentions before striking in future.
When am I not?

EditorData.NodeContext: convinced she is always right and stating it as amatter of fact

Text.Value: Not in the tower itself. There is more here than we see, but my mind only holds fragments of my time here.
In destroying the scroll, Jaheira has shown her readiness to give up the fight. We must not follow her example.
Orpheus believes it is his destiny to prevent the Grand Design. If he is willing to become illithid to do so, who are we to stand in his way?
The Emperor is the reason we have made it this far, and if the gith prince's suffering is the price of our survival, so be it.
Is the Absolute really here, in Moonrise?
Fascinating.

EditorData.NodeContext: it really isn't. She's already forgotten what she was told

Text.Value: Whatever her reasons for doing so, Jaheira's choice to keep the scroll shows that she is not ready to give up her fight.
We should hang up their remains as a warning to Cazador that you are under our protection, Astarion.
It is good to have friends in high places. We should keep the future Grand Duke Ravengard close.
Destroying the Absolute before we fully understand it would be madness.
The gith god-queen is dreadful to behold. I understand now why Lae'zel admires her.
Hope lives in the imagination. I prefer to deal in reality, and in our reality, Karlach is dying.
I believe you have your urges under control, for now, and that you may become the master of them.

EditorData.NodeContext: warning - she's concerned about the player's behaviour

Text.Value: And instead you have chosen to sever yourself from the legacy of blood that was your inheritance.
We need your strength to survive what is coming. I vow that you will have mine for as long as you can draw on it.
Like them, he will be true to his word, should we do as he asks, but he will stand to gain more than he gives.
When he is not with his troops, he is usually at the rooftop chapel, where he communes with the Absolute, while surveying his army from above.
We should not have held you back from your destiny, child. I am sorry.
Shadowheart could have been so much more than we have allowed her to be. This was not the time to hold her back.
I have something of a feline nature. I do not like getting wet, and I will gladly scratch out your eyes if you annoy me.
I never believed her until now.
This place is almost untouched by the squalor of the surface. If I ruled this city, this is where I would make my home.

EditorData.NodeContext: slight awe, self-satisfaction at having discovered a mysterious ancient dungeon beneath BAldur's Gate

Text.Value: The House of Healing might be a good place to scavenge medical supplies.
The gods are fickle. Mystra will tire of you again, as she did before.
I understand. If I had been told my death is close, as you have, I would rage.
This better be important. Every time I open my mouth, I taste the feculence of this place.
Your idea of charming is very different to mine.
We were wise to ally ourselves with Gortash. While Orin lives, she is the greatest threat to our survival - we must hunt her down and eliminate her.
An underground city of villains. It's almost like being home again.

EditorData.NodeContext: with a smile, she's making fun of her Underdark origins

Text.Value: Some True Souls are not fit to go to war. They act as guards in these lands, or spread the cult's influence through more insidious means than conquest.
I see. The end does justify the means. Be that as it may...
Murder, oppression, conspiracies. This city has its charms after all.
Even here, a child deserves a second chance.

EditorData.NodeContext: not spoken with a great deal of sympathy

Text.Value: You're right.
Let's stay on dry land from now on.
My people tell tales of Minsc and his ferocious hamster Boo to frighten our children.
Killing one's parents can be an important rite of passage - a usurpation of their place in society.

EditorData.NodeContext: genuinely believes this to be true

Text.Value: Devils, Dukes and Blades all must, as common people come to dust. Farewell, young Wyll.

EditorData.NodeContext: intentional rhyme, Wyll just died, and she's not particularly upset, but notes the occasion nonetheless

Text.Value: It does not mean he will be able to stop our design when the moment comes.

EditorData.NodeContext: malicious - 'our design' is to betray Orpheus and control the Absolute.

Text.Value: Why not take its head?
Little wonder the surface world is in such disarray if they are among its protectors.

EditorData.NodeContext: surprised by how feeble the harper 'network' is.

Text.Value: Despite the destitution, there is profit and opportunity to be found in such places if one is willing to wade through the squalor.

Then we have something in common.

EditorData.NodeContext: after seeing Karlach break down in tears after getting revenge on Gortash. GEnuinely sad

I fear you may be right.

EditorData.NodeContext: warning, she's losing her patience with you

EditorData.NodeContext: after the camp has been infiltrated by vampire spawn, annoyed to have been caught off-guard

Text.Value: We should return to Moonrise and search his chambers thoroughly - if we can learn anything of the relic there, it may arm us for what is to come.
What fun I would have if I could play with Wyll as Mizora does.
I presume you mean Gale? I'm a wizard too, you know.
I thought the vampire spawn would have needed an invitation to enter.

EditorData.NodeContext: after the camp has been infiltrated by vampire spawn, annoyed to have been caught off-guard

Text.Value: While we travel together, your business is my business.
Do as I would. Spend what time remains punishing our enemies.
A wizard should seek out knowledge and power, whatever the source.
Two hundred years ago, she disgraced her family - the DeVirs - by refusing to obey a divine order from Lolth.
I would have thought he'd seen enough of the place for several lifetimes, but he still visits on occasion.
She needs to pull herself together. We haven't won this fight yet.
Despite my antipathy to Viconia, I am sure she will aid us when the time comes.

EditorData.NodeContext: Viconia is a fellow drow from the same city as Minthara, they don't know each other well, but Minthara dislikes her

Text.Value: I see her grimace when Shar wracks her soul though, and I see the doubt in her eyes as the pain causes her to doubt the path she has taken.
If our travelling companions continue to make poor choices, we will soon have every god in this plane and the next hunting us.
I just want Cazador dead. Nothing more.
I presume you mean Gale? I'm a wizard too, you know.
Indeed. When my time comes, I do not think I will go quietly. Nor should you.
If she were here, Shadowheart would remind you that we are hardly trustworthy ourselves.
Wyll would be wiser to leverage his family name for a position of power in Baldur's Gate than to roam the wilds like some errant ranger.
Then that is what we must do.
Vengeance can be a bitter pill for a kind soul such as yours, Karlach. I pity you, that you can not savour Gortash's death.
The Crown of Karsus will be ours - the devil cannot have it. We must negate our deal with him by any means possible.
You embrace your illithid self. Good - to deny it is as foolish as denying any other possible advantage, whatever the source.
The shadows will take this place eventually, with or without our interference.

EditorData.NodeContext: matter of fact - she's not horrofied by the thoughts

Text.Value: Shadowheart was a fine cleric, but if her obsession with Shar is more important than the task at hand, we are better off without her.
You cannot seriously believe that?
I agree. It is a wizard's curiosity that drives them to greater heights.
It was a great victory - we should all celebrate.
Z'rell said we should begin our search at the Thorm Mausoleum. It is north of the House of Healing, deep in the shadows.
Your father - the Lord of Murder - offered you all of the powers of death and carnage. Powers that we will need before this fight is through.
That was the Absolute, and I sensed it is powerful enough to swallow the tower whole if it chooses to.
It's not for their favour - it was the right thing to do.
Don't tell me you're afraid of a little water.
The next urchin that tries to pick my pocket will lose its hand.
It would have been prudent to ally ourselves with Gortash. While Orin lives, she is the greatest threat to our survival.
The relationship between gods and mortals will always be one of subservience, but you could not hope for a finer master than Bhaal.
Perhaps a particle of sentimentality remains in Ketheric, and he mourns for his family. I do not know.
It's none of your business what I spend my hours doing.
It is not sentimental to appreciate a warrior's strength, or a companion's courage.
I had hoped the wizard may be intrigued by the arcane power of the shadow curse, but it seems he rejects it.
Once we have conquered the Absolute, perhaps we can turn our attention to dissolving the criminal elements of Baldur's Gate, and replacing them with our own candidates.

EditorData.NodeContext: superiority complex kicking into high gear as she assesses the chriminal organisations that run the city

Text.Value: I will be watching you - and watching for this 'butler' of yours as well.
Does your ambition match his, Astarion? You have risen from slavery already - perhaps you can complete your ascension.
You're only alive because I resisted the Urge to snap your neck the first time we lay together.
No. My indoctrination - my infection - took place at Moonrise, but I did not stay here for long.

EditorData.NodeContext: Bitterly correcting herself with the emphasis on 'infection'. That is the reality that she has recently remembered.

Text.Value: Our young cleric would have us believe she has found joy now that her parents are free.
Every breath here is painful - do not waste effort on idle words.

EditorData.NodeContext: in the shadowfell, a place that drains emotion. The 'pain' is due to that. Not overexaggerated, more an abrupt 'please don't talk right now' than any implied agony.

Text.Value: That is all.
Yes, but I know your name. His often escapes me.

EditorData.NodeContext: she doesn't remember Gale's name - and doesnt' see why she should

Text.Value: I would live forever if I could. Death is not rest or relief, it is only ever a form of defeat.
Raphael can beg for a deal all he wants - the Crown will be ours.
That I was willing - honoured even - to lead a pack of goblins in the Absolute's name is proof enough that I did not know my own mind.
Strange that the cult gathers its forces in such a hostile place.
Be cautious. The slightest mistake here could cost us our freedom, or our lives.

EditorData.NodeContext: quietly but not whispered, spoken in Moonrise, a dangerous place

Text.Value: I was ready to rule by your side, Slayer. But you have given up a most glorious and dishonourable birthright. We are finished.
You insult me. Viconia left the Underdark to rule a clergy of mournful waifs, and peddlers of secrets. I have far grander ambitions.
We paid the price for your thrills when the shadows surrounded us. If you must kill for the pleasure of it, select your targets more carefully.
I would prefer him to explore the possibilities of the shadow magic.
Isobel and the Harpers would have realised we're a threat to them eventually.
You know what must be done. Transform. Evolve.
Though she does not remember what she has done, the child Shadowheart became a proud woman today. And a strong leader.
We walk on unholy ground.
Must we talk? The heat is unbearable - my mouth is as dry as a dust devil.

EditorData.NodeContext: no exaggerated coughs or splutters - she's irritated though. Spoken while visiting hell - it's hot!

Text.Value: If it is Mystra's will, I must obey.
The kind of man who sees death as a problem to solve rather than an inevitable truth.
My sense of self-preservation outmuscled it on this occasion.
Mystra has chosen to bless me for my efforts against the shadow magic in these parts.
Lae'zel risks our safety. If she attracts the ire of Vlaakith, we will all suffer.
I admire those who challenge authority, but Viconia fled from her troubles rather than facing them.
It is my duty to seek out knowledge, whatever the source.
I am suggesting that you consider the possibility.
It does not surprise me that your faith in Shar was based on a lie. You will have your vengeance.
It does not surprise me that Shadowheart's faith was based on a lie. Deception is the sum of Shar's design.
I could not agree more. The pursuit of knowledge and power should always be our goal.
There has never been a need to.
Life is conflict. Coddling children, and denying them that truth only makes them weak.

EditorData.NodeContext: first phrase is the core of her philosophy. She truly believes this

Text.Value: I am reminded of The Braeryn, the Stenchstreets of Menzoberranzan where the sick and the outlawed make their homes.
You're paranoid. Nobody's trying to pick your pocket.
I am surprised you have time to bother me, wizard. You seem to be spending most of your hours pining after Mystra again.
Now, return to your books. We have a city to save, and an elder brain to master.

EditorData.NodeContext: just complimented Gale and is trying to ground him in reality again so he doesn't get too pompous, and so SHE doesn't seem too soft
